I think a lot about how the Millennials were the last generation that could build relationships with artists without being expected to critically view them.
We grew up in a golden age of media, with a collective awareness of pop culture that no longer exists.
We could dive into things without having to think about where they came from, because back then you couldn't easily determine that anyway.
We didn't have to question the pedestal we put them on. These parasocial relationships were so important and influenced our lives.
That's why we have such a strong tendency towards nostalgia.
When "The Office" was still on air, my friends and I ordered pizza every Thursday and watched the show together.
That was completely different from today with streaming, where 12 episodes come out all at once and everyone watches whenever they feel like it, and social media posts come with "spoiler warnings" or discuss them in closed groups.
Subconsciously, we long for this universal community that used to dominate everything.
That's why so many of us still watch shows like "The Office" or movies like "Anchorman," in which so many one-liners would be memes today.
We all brought these catchphrases and assumed that most people already understood them.
Today, you can no longer assume that everyone knows something, even if it spreads virally on a massive scale.
There's just too much, and there's no way to systematize it. Will we ever get out of this saturation?
We're trapped in a cycle of constantly discovering new content, only to realize afterward that the artist is greedy or a hypocrite.
That's why we have to hold on to our nostalgia while also accepting that the people who created the works we liked can also have made big mistakes.
We enter parasocial relationships with greater caution.
We are aware that it's hard to become rich and powerful without stepping on a few toes along the way.
Since our collective awareness regarding media has disappeared, we have developed a class consciousness that promotes critical thinking.
There are still those among us who put someone on a pedestal, only to be shocked when they fall from it.
We are in a period of transition and I'm curious to see where it will ultimately lead.
